the vali & nominators receive 41% of the emissions. at the beginning, root has 100% proportion of the divs, so they receive all of that 41% or 0.41. as root proportion lowers, the amount they receive and sell lowers. 0.40, 0.39, 0.38, etc. and at the same time, the divs for the subnet nominators & valis go up. 0.01, 0.02, 0.03, etc. 

once root proportion is less than 50%, the subnet nominators & valis will begin receiving more divs than what root can sell. e.g. 0.21 for power users, 0.2 for root. 0.22 for power users, 0.19 for root etc etc

root proportion trends to zero over time, and alpha proportion trends to 100% over time

we use 50% because that's basically the inflection point. at that point, tao in the pool begins trending upwards as it overcomes the root sell pressure, and the price trends upward as well. the price converges towards the emissions when price < emission. if price > emission, the price would stabilize, and you do this by adjusting the alpha_in per block for that subnet. only the market can push that price down towards the emissions. otherwise, it stabilizes

the sum of the prices doesn't need to be 1. however, when the sum of the prices is less than 1, then eventually it will rebound back to one because of the rules above. but it's not gonna happen until the massive sell pressure from root goes away

EMA price / sum of EMA prices = tao_in

tao_in / price = alpha_in

when price < tao_in, the alpha_in is greater than 1. so it has to be scaled down to 1. the price converges towards tao_in
